1
00:00:10,594 --> 00:00:12,137
POSTMAN: Morning, love.
WOMAN: Morning.

2
00:00:20,437 --> 00:00:21,897
WOMAN: Hiya!
MAN: All right.

3
00:00:49,466 --> 00:00:51,635
Maeve? You okay?

4
00:00:52,928 --> 00:00:55,097
No, love, I'm not.

5
00:00:55,180 --> 00:00:58,100
-You want me to call a doctor?
-Doctor can't help.

6
00:00:58,976 --> 00:01:03,146
Can't you... Can't you feel it, Trish?

7
00:01:03,230 --> 00:01:05,023
Can't feel anything.

8
00:01:05,732 --> 00:01:10,904
Boys! Get indoors! Get inside!
Get 'em inside!

9
00:01:10,988 --> 00:01:12,656
What's up with you?
They ain't done nothing wrong.

10
00:01:12,739 --> 00:01:14,616
MAEVE: It's happening again!

11
00:01:17,077 --> 00:01:19,997
GIRL: # ...sits in the old gum tree

12
00:01:20,372 --> 00:01:24,501
# Merry merry king of the bush is he

13
00:01:24,585 --> 00:01:28,755
# Laugh, kookaburra, laugh, kookaburra

14
00:01:28,839 --> 00:01:31,883
# Gay your life must be #

15
00:01:37,973 --> 00:01:40,392
-They're not safe.
-They're in the garden.

16
00:01:40,517 --> 00:01:43,186
That's what it likes.
It likes it when they're playing.

17
00:01:43,270 --> 00:01:45,230
Get 'em in, I'm begging you!

18
00:01:45,355 --> 00:01:49,776
# Merry merry king of the bush is he

19
00:01:50,360 --> 00:01:55,115
# Laugh, kookaburra, laugh, kookaburra

20
00:01:55,198 --> 00:01:58,201
# Gay your life must be #

21
00:01:58,327 --> 00:02:02,539
Right, I've got my beady eyes on them.
Come on, come on.

22
00:02:04,583 --> 00:02:07,210
MAEVE: No!
MAN: Tom?

23
00:02:07,586 --> 00:02:10,130
-MAEVE: What are you?
-Where's he gone?

24
00:02:10,213 --> 00:02:13,258
MAEVE: What do you want
with our children?

25
00:02:13,342 --> 00:02:16,303
(HUMMING)

26
00:02:19,389 --> 00:02:21,224
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

27
00:02:59,638 --> 00:03:02,557
(WHOOSHING)

28
00:03:06,603 --> 00:03:07,771
Ah.

29
00:03:10,357 --> 00:03:12,693
(WHOOSHING)

30
00:03:19,116 --> 00:03:20,742
Ah!

31
00:03:22,494 --> 00:03:24,037
(DRILLING)

32
00:03:28,625 --> 00:03:30,585
So, near future, yeah?

33
00:03:31,294 --> 00:03:34,214
I had a passing fancy.
Only, it didn't pass, it stopped.

34
00:03:35,924 --> 00:03:39,970
-30th Olympiad.
-No way! Why didn't I think of this?

35
00:03:40,095 --> 00:03:41,471
That's great. Aw!

36
00:03:41,638 --> 00:03:42,931
DOCTOR: Only seems like yesterday

37
00:03:43,014 --> 00:03:46,101
a few naked Greek blokes
were tossing a discus about,

38
00:03:46,226 --> 00:03:49,438
wrestling with each other in the sand,
as the crowds stood around baying...

39
00:03:49,521 --> 00:03:51,815
No, wait a minute, that was Club Med.

40
00:03:52,357 --> 00:03:55,193
Just in time
for the opening doodah ceremony tonight.

41
00:03:55,277 --> 00:03:57,571
I thought you'd like that.
Last one they had in London was dynamite.

42
00:03:57,654 --> 00:03:58,864
Wembley, 1948.

43
00:03:58,989 --> 00:04:01,199
I loved it so much I went back
and watched it all over again.

44
00:04:01,324 --> 00:04:06,747
Fella carrying a torch. Lovely chap.
What was his... Mark? John, Mark?

45
00:04:06,830 --> 00:04:08,081
Legs like pipe-cleaners,

46
00:04:08,165 --> 00:04:09,374
-but strong as a whippet...
-Doctor...

47
00:04:09,499 --> 00:04:11,585
And in those days,
everyone had a tea party to go to...

48
00:04:11,668 --> 00:04:13,170
-Doctor!
-You ever have those little cakes

49
00:04:13,253 --> 00:04:15,756
-with the crunchy ball bearings on top?
-You should really look at this!

50
00:04:15,839 --> 00:04:17,132
You know those things?

51
00:04:17,215 --> 00:04:18,633
Nobody else in this entire galaxy

52
00:04:18,717 --> 00:04:21,970
has ever even bothered
to make edible ball bearings. Genius!

53
00:04:23,680 --> 00:04:25,766
DOCTOR: Who's taken them, do you think?

54
00:04:29,144 --> 00:04:32,272
Snatching children
from a thoroughly ordinary street like this.

55
00:04:33,440 --> 00:04:35,817
And why is it so cold?

56
00:04:36,526 --> 00:04:38,528
Someone reducing the temperature?

57
00:04:38,862 --> 00:04:41,072
ROSE: Says here he went missing
this week.

58
00:04:43,116 --> 00:04:46,119
Why would a person
do something like this?

59
00:04:46,203 --> 00:04:47,621
What makes you think it's a person?

60
00:04:47,704 --> 00:04:48,830
(DOOR OPENING)

61
00:04:49,873 --> 00:04:53,335
ROSE: Whatever it is,
it's got the whole street scared to death.

62
00:04:55,462 --> 00:04:57,005
Doctor, what...

63
00:05:17,984 --> 00:05:21,154
(CAR ENGINE FALTERING)

64
00:05:25,492 --> 00:05:29,454
There you go. Fifth today.
That's not natural, is it?

65
00:05:29,538 --> 00:05:32,165
Dunno what happened.
I had it serviced less than a month ago.

66
00:05:32,249 --> 00:05:34,084
Nah, don't even try and explain it, mate.

67
00:05:34,167 --> 00:05:36,378
All the cars are doing it,
and you know what?

68
00:05:36,461 --> 00:05:39,172
It's bonkers. Bonkers.

69
00:05:39,297 --> 00:05:41,591
Come on then, pal, I'll help you shift it.

70
00:05:41,800 --> 00:05:44,594
Quicker you're on your way,
happier you'll be.

71
00:05:47,472 --> 00:05:49,182
(GRUNTING) There we go.

72
00:05:50,100 --> 00:05:52,936
-Do you want a hand?
-No, we're all right, love.

73
00:05:53,812 --> 00:05:55,105
Well, you're not.

74
00:05:55,230 --> 00:05:57,065
I'm tougher than I look. Honest.

75
00:06:00,443 --> 00:06:03,280
(CAR ENGINE STARTING)

76
00:06:05,115 --> 00:06:07,242
-Does this happen a lot?
-DRIVER: Cheers, mate!

77
00:06:08,034 --> 00:06:09,786
(SIGHING) Been doing it all week.

78
00:06:09,953 --> 00:06:13,039
Since those children started going missing?

79
00:06:13,123 --> 00:06:15,625
Yeah. Suppose so.

80
00:06:15,917 --> 00:06:18,962
Hmm. Tickles.

81
00:06:23,717 --> 00:06:25,635
What's your game?

82
00:06:25,886 --> 00:06:27,554
My... Um...

83
00:06:28,305 --> 00:06:32,100
Snakes and ladders.
Quite good at squash, reasonable...

84
00:06:32,642 --> 00:06:35,645
I'm being facetious, aren't I?

85
00:06:35,729 --> 00:06:37,480
There's no call for it.

86
00:06:37,606 --> 00:06:39,107
Every car cuts out.

87
00:06:39,232 --> 00:06:40,483
Council are going nuts.

88
00:06:40,567 --> 00:06:43,153
I mean, they've given this street the works.
Renamed it.

89
00:06:43,278 --> 00:06:45,155
I've been tarmacking every pothole.

90
00:06:45,322 --> 00:06:47,407
Look at that. Beauty, innit?

91
00:06:47,490 --> 00:06:48,617
Yep.

92
00:06:48,700 --> 00:06:51,953
And all this is because that Olympic torch
comes right by the end of this close.

93
00:06:52,037 --> 00:06:53,330
Just down there.

94
00:06:53,496 --> 00:06:55,832
Everything's gotta be perfect, ain't it?

95
00:06:56,041 --> 00:06:59,252
-KEL: Only it ain't.
-It takes 'em when they're playing.

96
00:06:59,419 --> 00:07:02,631
-What takes them?
-Danny, Jane, Dale,

97
00:07:02,714 --> 00:07:04,466
-snatched in the blink of an eye.
-MAN: Liar! You're a liar!

98
00:07:04,549 --> 00:07:06,092
DOCTOR: I am a... I'm a... Police officer!

99
00:07:06,176 --> 00:07:09,763
That's what I am.
I've got a badge and a police car.

100
00:07:09,846 --> 00:07:11,765
You don't have to get... I can prove it.
Just hold on...

101
00:07:11,848 --> 00:07:13,266
We've had plenty of coppers
poking round here,

102
00:07:13,350 --> 00:07:15,101
and you don't look or sound like any of 'em.

103
00:07:15,185 --> 00:07:17,145
See? Look, I got a colleague! Lewis.

104
00:07:17,228 --> 00:07:18,813
Well, she looks less
like a copper than you do.

105
00:07:18,897 --> 00:07:20,190
Training. New recruit.

106
00:07:20,273 --> 00:07:22,692
It was either that or hairdressing.
So... Voila!

107
00:07:23,401 --> 00:07:27,280
-What are you going to do?
-The police have knocked on every door.

108
00:07:27,364 --> 00:07:29,574
No clues, no leads, nothing!

109
00:07:29,658 --> 00:07:31,409
Look, look, kids run off sometimes,
all right?

110
00:07:31,534 --> 00:07:34,287
-That's what they do.
-I saw it with me own eyes.

111
00:07:34,371 --> 00:07:38,208
Dale Hicks in your garden
playing with your Tommy, and then...

112
00:07:39,042 --> 00:07:42,837
Right in front of me,
like he was never there.

113
00:07:42,921 --> 00:07:45,590
There's no need
to look any further than this street.

114
00:07:45,674 --> 00:07:47,467
It's right here amongst us!

115
00:07:47,550 --> 00:07:49,970
-Why don't we...
-Why don't we start with him!

116
00:07:50,053 --> 00:07:52,973
There's been all sorts like him
in this street, day and night...

117
00:07:53,056 --> 00:07:54,641
Fixing things up for the Olympics!

118
00:07:54,724 --> 00:07:56,184
Yeah, and taking
an awful long time about it!

119
00:07:56,267 --> 00:07:58,019
I'm of the opinion
that all we've gotta do is...

120
00:07:58,103 --> 00:07:59,187
That woman who just said... That's slander!

121
00:07:59,270 --> 00:08:00,480
I don't care what it is!

122
00:08:00,563 --> 00:08:01,648
I think we need to just...

123
00:08:01,731 --> 00:08:04,651
-I want an apology off her!
-Stop picking on him!

124
00:08:04,734 --> 00:08:08,196
-Yeah! Stop picking on me!
-MAEVE: And stop pretending to be blind!

125
00:08:08,279 --> 00:08:10,281
-It's evil!
-I don't believe in evil.

126
00:08:10,365 --> 00:08:12,033
Oh, no! You just believe in tarmackers

127
00:08:12,117 --> 00:08:13,868
with sack-loads of kidnapped kiddies
in their van.

128
00:08:13,952 --> 00:08:16,538
-Hey, hey, that's not what she's saying!
-Would you stop ganging up on me?

129
00:08:16,621 --> 00:08:18,081
Feeling guilty, are we?

130
00:08:18,164 --> 00:08:20,291
Fingers on lips!

131
00:08:29,884 --> 00:08:33,263
In the last six days,
three of your children have been stolen,

132
00:08:34,139 --> 00:08:36,141
snatched out of thin air, right?

133
00:08:38,268 --> 00:08:40,228
Uh... Can I...

134
00:08:42,105 --> 00:08:43,690
Look around you.

135
00:08:44,149 --> 00:08:47,235
This was a safe street till it came.

136
00:08:47,569 --> 00:08:49,404
It's not a person.

137
00:08:49,654 --> 00:08:51,906
I'll say it if no one else will.

138
00:08:52,073 --> 00:08:54,492
Maybe you're coppers, maybe you're not.

139
00:08:54,617 --> 00:08:59,164
I don't care who you are.
Can you please help us?

140
00:09:08,840 --> 00:09:11,968
(DOCTOR SNIFFING)

141
00:09:21,311 --> 00:09:23,188
-Want a hanky?
-You smell it?

142
00:09:24,564 --> 00:09:26,566
What's it remind you of?

143
00:09:26,649 --> 00:09:28,568
Sort of metal?

144
00:09:28,651 --> 00:09:30,153
-Mmm-hmm.
-Oh!

145
00:09:33,114 --> 00:09:36,493
Danny Edwards cycled in one end
but never came out the other.

146
00:09:36,576 --> 00:09:38,745
Whoa! There it goes again.

147
00:09:39,579 --> 00:09:41,664
Look at the hairs on the back
of my manly hairy hand.

148
00:09:41,790 --> 00:09:47,462
And there's that smell.
It's like a burnt fuse plug or something.

149
00:09:47,879 --> 00:09:51,174
There's a residual energy in the spots
where the kids vanished.

150
00:09:51,257 --> 00:09:55,261
Whatever it was,
it used an awful lot of power to do this.

151
00:09:58,515 --> 00:09:59,849
(MEWING)

152
00:10:04,187 --> 00:10:07,315
-You have to come down sometime, Chloe.
-I'm busy, Mum.

153
00:10:09,275 --> 00:10:10,652
Look at it in here.

154
00:10:10,735 --> 00:10:14,447
Must've used up half a rain forest.
That's Dale.

155
00:10:17,450 --> 00:10:21,329
-Why did you draw him so sad?
-I didn't draw him like that.

156
00:10:23,164 --> 00:10:25,917
Dale made himself sad,

157
00:10:26,042 --> 00:10:27,919
so I'm gonna draw him a friend.

158
00:10:28,002 --> 00:10:30,713
That's what he needs, more friends.

159
00:10:34,551 --> 00:10:36,761
Have you seen the TV?

160
00:10:37,178 --> 00:10:40,181
Look, this'll cheer you up.
The torch is getting close.

161
00:10:40,306 --> 00:10:42,350
It'll pass right by our street.

162
00:10:42,433 --> 00:10:45,103
And tonight they'll light the Olympic flame
in the stadium,

163
00:10:45,228 --> 00:10:47,355
and the whole world
will be looking at our city.

164
00:10:47,438 --> 00:10:49,023
MAN ON TV: ...they're lining the street...

165
00:10:49,107 --> 00:10:51,818
I mean, doesn't that make you feel
part of something?

166
00:10:51,901 --> 00:10:52,986
Sweetheart?

167
00:10:53,069 --> 00:10:55,822
We've seen the Prime Minister,
we've seen members of the Royal family...

168
00:10:55,905 --> 00:10:57,657
-Chloe?
-I'm busy, Mum.

169
00:10:57,740 --> 00:10:59,242
-Okay.
-...as young Danny Fairweather

170
00:10:59,325 --> 00:11:02,829
carries the torch past them
on this wonderful summer's day.

171
00:11:02,912 --> 00:11:06,291
Very fitting. We've seen lots
of our sporting royalty, too...

172
00:11:06,416 --> 00:11:10,378
You're tired, Chloe.
I heard you calling out again last night.

173
00:11:10,461 --> 00:11:12,755
-It's fine.
-Nightmares?

174
00:11:12,839 --> 00:11:14,048
I'm drawing.

175
00:11:14,132 --> 00:11:15,675
MAN ON TV: Let me remind you
where the torches come from...

176
00:11:15,758 --> 00:11:16,843
Whatever they are...

177
00:11:16,926 --> 00:11:18,052
...journey from the temple of...

178
00:11:18,136 --> 00:11:20,680
...they're just dreams. You do know that?

179
00:11:21,931 --> 00:11:24,184
-They can't hurt you.
-I'm busy.

180
00:11:24,267 --> 00:11:27,604
Unless you want me to draw you,

181
00:11:27,729 --> 00:11:28,771
Mum.

182
00:11:30,273 --> 00:11:33,943
If you wanna stay cooped up in here, fine.
I'll leave you to it.

183
00:11:37,864 --> 00:11:40,909
-Oh, aren't you a beautiful boy!
-Thanks!

184
00:11:40,992 --> 00:11:43,036
I'm experimenting with backcombing. Oh.

185
00:11:43,119 --> 00:11:44,621
I used to have one like you.

186
00:11:44,746 --> 00:11:46,080
(CAT MEWING)

187
00:11:47,999 --> 00:11:49,042
What?

188
00:11:49,792 --> 00:11:52,170
No, I'm not really a cat person.

189
00:11:53,046 --> 00:11:54,756
Once you've been threatened by one
in a nun's wimple,

190
00:11:54,839 --> 00:11:56,299
kind of takes the joy out of it.

191
00:11:56,382 --> 00:11:57,634
(CAT MEWS)

192
00:11:57,967 --> 00:11:59,093
Come here, puss.

193
00:12:01,429 --> 00:12:03,306
What do you wanna go in there for?

194
00:12:15,693 --> 00:12:16,819
Doctor.

195
00:12:22,158 --> 00:12:23,159
Whoa!

196
00:12:23,243 --> 00:12:24,911
(EXCLAIMING)

197
00:12:26,162 --> 00:12:28,248
Ion residue. Blimey!

198
00:12:28,373 --> 00:12:29,415
(DOCTOR EXCLAIMS)

199
00:12:29,499 --> 00:12:30,583
That takes some doing.

200
00:12:30,667 --> 00:12:32,585
Just to snatch
a living organism out of space-time.

201
00:12:32,669 --> 00:12:35,755
This baby is just like,
"I'm having some of that!" I'm impressed.

202
00:12:35,838 --> 00:12:37,257
So the cat's been transported?

203
00:12:37,340 --> 00:12:39,968
It can harness huge reserves
of ionic power.

204
00:12:40,385 --> 00:12:42,929
We need to find the source of that power.

205
00:12:43,346 --> 00:12:45,390
Find the source and you will find

206
00:12:45,473 --> 00:12:48,518
whatever has taken to stealing children
and fluffy animals.

207
00:12:48,601 --> 00:12:51,562
See what you can see.
Keep 'em peeled, Lewis.

208
00:12:53,356 --> 00:12:56,025
I've given you friends, and you still moan.

209
00:12:56,109 --> 00:12:59,279
Moan, moan, moan. You're lucky.

210
00:12:59,362 --> 00:13:02,615
You're all together.
You don't know what it is to be alone.

211
00:13:02,782 --> 00:13:05,368
If you did, you'd be thanking me.

212
00:13:09,539 --> 00:13:10,665
(PENCIL SNAPS)

213
00:13:10,748 --> 00:13:12,166
No!

214
00:13:16,337 --> 00:13:17,630
(DOG BARKING)

215
00:13:24,512 --> 00:13:25,722
(THUDDING)

216
00:13:25,972 --> 00:13:27,181
(METALLIC CLINKING)

217
00:13:37,608 --> 00:13:38,776
(THUDDING)

218
00:13:38,901 --> 00:13:40,862
That you, puss cat? You trapped?

219
00:13:42,655 --> 00:13:45,450
(METALLIC CLINKING)

220
00:13:46,326 --> 00:13:48,369
(CRASHING)

221
00:13:50,121 --> 00:13:53,583
Not gonna open it, not gonna open it.
Not gonna open it...

222
00:14:11,476 --> 00:14:13,811
(BUZZING)

223
00:14:16,272 --> 00:14:17,607
Stay still!

224
00:14:22,612 --> 00:14:23,988
Okey do key?

225
00:14:25,031 --> 00:14:28,159
-Yeah. Cheers.
-No probs.

226
00:14:28,534 --> 00:14:30,203
(EXCLAIMS IN RELIEF)

227
00:14:30,953 --> 00:14:32,997
I'll give you a fiver if you can tell me
what the hell it is.

228
00:14:33,081 --> 00:14:35,375
'Cause I haven't got the foggiest.

229
00:14:35,458 --> 00:14:38,795
-Well, I can tell you you just killed it.
-It was never living.

230
00:14:38,878 --> 00:14:40,380
It's animated by energy.

231
00:14:40,630 --> 00:14:43,508
The same energy that's snatching people.
That is so dinky!

232
00:14:43,591 --> 00:14:46,260
The go-anywhere creature.
Fits in your pocket.

233
00:14:46,344 --> 00:14:49,055
Makes friends, impresses the boss,
breaks the ice at parties.

234
00:14:49,138 --> 00:14:50,473
(LAUGHING)

235
00:14:50,556 --> 00:14:53,184
DOCTOR: Oh. Hi-oh. Here we go.
Let's have a look.

236
00:14:55,603 --> 00:14:58,147
-Get out of here!
-What's it say?

237
00:15:04,987 --> 00:15:06,197
It is.

238
00:15:06,989 --> 00:15:08,991
It's graphite.

239
00:15:09,158 --> 00:15:12,161
Basically, the same material
as an HB pencil.

240
00:15:12,286 --> 00:15:16,165
-I was attacked by a pencil scribble?
-A scribble creature.

241
00:15:16,249 --> 00:15:18,376
Brought into being with ionic energy.

242
00:15:19,001 --> 00:15:21,712
Whatever we're dealing with,
it can create things as well as take them.

243
00:15:21,796 --> 00:15:24,632
But why make a scribble creature?

244
00:15:24,924 --> 00:15:26,509
Maybe it was a mistake.

245
00:15:26,592 --> 00:15:28,845
I mean, you scribble over something
when you wanna get rid of it,

246
00:15:28,928 --> 00:15:32,056
like a drawing. Like a...

247
00:15:33,349 --> 00:15:35,476
child's drawing.

248
00:15:36,936 --> 00:15:39,188
-He said it was in the street.
-Probably.

249
00:15:39,355 --> 00:15:41,691
-The girl.
-Of course! What girl?

250
00:15:41,774 --> 00:15:43,818
Something about her gave me the creeps.

251
00:15:43,901 --> 00:15:46,112
Even her own mum looked scared of her.

252
00:15:46,195 --> 00:15:49,699
-Are you deducting?
-I think I am.

253
00:15:49,782 --> 00:15:52,368
-Copper's hunch?
-Permission to follow it up, Sarge.

254
00:15:52,827 --> 00:15:54,078
(DOORBELL RINGING)

255
00:16:00,084 --> 00:16:01,210
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

256
00:16:06,883 --> 00:16:10,344
Hello. I'm the Doctor and this is Rose.
Can we see your daughter?

257
00:16:10,428 --> 00:16:13,222
-No. You can't.
-Okay. Bye.

258
00:16:15,349 --> 00:16:18,144
Why? Why do you want to see Chloe?

259
00:16:18,478 --> 00:16:20,480
Well, there's some interesting stuff
going on in this street,

260
00:16:20,563 --> 00:16:21,731
and I just thought...

261
00:16:21,814 --> 00:16:24,859
Well, we thought that she might like
to give us a hand.

262
00:16:24,942 --> 00:16:27,195
-Sorry to bother you.
-Yeah. Sorry.

263
00:16:27,278 --> 00:16:30,907
We'll let you get on with things.
On your own. Bye again.

264
00:16:31,908 --> 00:16:33,409
Wait.

265
00:16:36,621 --> 00:16:38,789
Can you help her?

266
00:16:39,749 --> 00:16:40,917
Yes, I can.

267
00:16:41,042 --> 00:16:45,213
MAN ON TV: The torchbearer
ls running up towards the Mall...

268
00:16:45,296 --> 00:16:47,798
She stays in her room most of the time.

269
00:16:47,882 --> 00:16:51,928
I try talking to her,
but it's like trying to speak to a brick wall.

270
00:16:53,471 --> 00:16:56,098
She gives me nothing,
just asks to be left alone.

271
00:16:57,183 --> 00:17:00,019
What about Chloe's dad?

272
00:17:00,102 --> 00:17:03,397
-Chloe's dad died a year ago.
-I'm sorry.

273
00:17:04,315 --> 00:17:05,900
You wouldn't be if you'd known him.

274
00:17:06,484 --> 00:17:08,444
Well, let's go and say hi.

275
00:17:09,320 --> 00:17:12,156
I should check on her first,
she might be asleep.

276
00:17:13,115 --> 00:17:15,117
Why are you afraid of her, Trish?

277
00:17:17,119 --> 00:17:20,414
I want you to know, before you see her,
that she's really a great kid.

278
00:17:20,498 --> 00:17:21,624
I'm sure she is.

279
00:17:21,707 --> 00:17:22,792
Yeah.

280
00:17:22,875 --> 00:17:24,961
She's never been in trouble at school.

281
00:17:25,086 --> 00:17:27,296
You should see her report from last year.

282
00:17:27,380 --> 00:17:28,714
A's and B's.

283
00:17:31,092 --> 00:17:32,760
Can I use your loo?

284
00:17:37,974 --> 00:17:40,560
She's in the choir.

285
00:17:40,643 --> 00:17:44,564
She sings in an old folks' home.
Any mum would be proud, you know?

286
00:17:44,814 --> 00:17:48,317
I want you to know these things
before you see her, Doctor,

287
00:17:48,401 --> 00:17:50,486
because right now, she's not herself.

288
00:18:42,705 --> 00:18:45,041
(DOOR RATTLING)

289
00:19:01,057 --> 00:19:02,516
All right there?

290
00:19:07,563 --> 00:19:09,565
I'm the Doctor.

291
00:19:10,441 --> 00:19:11,651
I'm Chloe Webber.

292
00:19:11,734 --> 00:19:14,070
-How you doing, Chloe Webber?
-I'm busy.

293
00:19:14,153 --> 00:19:15,613
I'm making something.

294
00:19:15,696 --> 00:19:17,323
Aren't I, Mum?

295
00:19:17,406 --> 00:19:19,909
And like I said, she's not been sleeping...

296
00:19:20,076 --> 00:19:21,827
But you've been drawing, though.

297
00:19:22,328 --> 00:19:25,873
I'm rubbish. Stickmen about my limit.

298
00:19:25,956 --> 00:19:27,249
I can do this, though.

299
00:19:28,417 --> 00:19:29,919
Can you do that?

300
00:19:31,212 --> 00:19:33,506
-They don't stop moaning.
-TRISH: Chloe...

301
00:19:33,589 --> 00:19:36,884
I try to help them,
but they don't stop moaning.

302
00:19:37,176 --> 00:19:38,344
Who don't?

303
00:19:38,427 --> 00:19:40,846
-We can be together.
-Sweetheart...

304
00:19:40,930 --> 00:19:42,390
Don't touch me, Mum.

305
00:19:45,893 --> 00:19:47,812
(DOOR RATTLING)

306
00:20:16,298 --> 00:20:17,967
SINISTER VOICE: I'm coming...

307
00:20:18,050 --> 00:20:20,386
I'm busy, Doctor.

308
00:20:20,469 --> 00:20:23,097
Come on, Chloe, don't be a spoilsport.

309
00:20:23,180 --> 00:20:24,640
What's the big project?

310
00:20:25,349 --> 00:20:28,352
I'm dying to know.
What you making up there?

311
00:20:28,477 --> 00:20:29,729
ROSE: Doctor!

312
00:20:32,565 --> 00:20:35,276
SINISTER VOICE: I'm coming to hurt you...

313
00:20:37,278 --> 00:20:39,321
-Look at it.
-No, ta.

314
00:20:39,405 --> 00:20:42,199
-What the hell was that?
-ROSE: Drawing. Face of a man...

315
00:20:42,324 --> 00:20:44,118
-What face?
-Best not.

316
00:20:44,201 --> 00:20:45,619
What have you been drawing?

317
00:20:45,703 --> 00:20:47,872
-I drew him yesterday.
-Who?

318
00:20:47,997 --> 00:20:50,166
-Dad.
-TRISH: Your dad?

319
00:20:50,291 --> 00:20:52,209
But he's long gone.

320
00:20:52,460 --> 00:20:55,546
Chloe, with all the lovely things
in the world, why him?

321
00:20:55,629 --> 00:20:58,048
I dream about him staring at me.

322
00:20:58,132 --> 00:21:00,384
I thought we were putting him behind us.

323
00:21:00,468 --> 00:21:02,178
What's the matter with you?

324
00:21:02,261 --> 00:21:04,764
-We need to stay together.
-Yes, we do.

325
00:21:04,847 --> 00:21:07,767
No, not you. Us.

326
00:21:08,434 --> 00:21:11,520
We need to stay together,
and then it'll be all right.

327
00:21:13,606 --> 00:21:15,274
Trish, the drawings,

328
00:21:15,357 --> 00:21:17,109
have you seen
what Chloe's drawings can do?

329
00:21:17,193 --> 00:21:18,861
Who gave you permission
to come into her room?

330
00:21:18,986 --> 00:21:20,404
Get out of my house.

331
00:21:20,529 --> 00:21:21,864
Tell us about the drawings, Chloe.

332
00:21:21,989 --> 00:21:23,199
I don't want to hear any more of this.

333
00:21:23,282 --> 00:21:24,825
But that drawing of her dad...

334
00:21:24,909 --> 00:21:27,244
-I heard a voice, he spoke.
-He's dead.

335
00:21:27,328 --> 00:21:29,205
And these? They're kid's pictures.
Now get out!

336
00:21:29,288 --> 00:21:30,706
Chloe has a power.

337
00:21:30,790 --> 00:21:34,293
And I don't know how,
but she used it to take Danny Edwards,

338
00:21:34,376 --> 00:21:36,629
Dale Hicks.
She's using it to snatch the kids.

339
00:21:36,712 --> 00:21:38,714
-Get out.
-Have you seen those drawings move?

340
00:21:38,798 --> 00:21:41,217
-I haven't seen anything.
-Yes, you have.

341
00:21:41,300 --> 00:21:42,968
-Out of the corner of your eye.
-No.

342
00:21:43,052 --> 00:21:45,054
And you dismissed it,
because what choice do you have?

343
00:21:45,137 --> 00:21:46,889
When you see something
you can't possibly explain,

344
00:21:46,972 --> 00:21:49,350
you dismiss it, right?
And if anyone mentions it, you get angry.

345
00:21:49,433 --> 00:21:52,061
-So it's never spoken of ever again.
-She's a child.

346
00:21:52,144 --> 00:21:53,646
And you're terrified of her.

347
00:21:53,729 --> 00:21:55,564
But there's no one to turn to,
"cause who's gonna believe

348
00:21:55,689 --> 00:21:58,359
the things you see
out of the corner of your eye? No one.

349
00:21:58,442 --> 00:21:59,568
Except me.

350
00:22:00,986 --> 00:22:02,404
Who are you?

351
00:22:03,322 --> 00:22:04,698
I'm help.

352
00:22:08,410 --> 00:22:09,995
(ROSE CLEARS THROAT)

353
00:22:17,419 --> 00:22:19,296
Those pictures, they're alive.

354
00:22:19,380 --> 00:22:21,924
She's drawing people
and they end up in her pictures.

355
00:22:22,007 --> 00:22:24,301
Ionic energy.
Chloe's harnessing it to steal those kids

356
00:22:24,385 --> 00:22:27,137
and place them in some kind of holding pen
made up of ionic power.

357
00:22:27,263 --> 00:22:29,265
And what about the dad from hell
in her wardrobe?

358
00:22:29,348 --> 00:22:31,809
How many times do I have to tell you?
He's dead.

359
00:22:32,268 --> 00:22:35,646
Well, he's got a very loud voice
for a dead bloke.

360
00:22:35,729 --> 00:22:37,898
If living things can become drawings,

361
00:22:37,982 --> 00:22:40,609
then maybe drawings
can become living things.

362
00:22:41,485 --> 00:22:42,820
(EXCLAIMS IN FEAR)

363
00:22:43,404 --> 00:22:44,697
Chloe's real dad is dead,

364
00:22:44,780 --> 00:22:46,615
but not the one who visits her
in her nightmares.

365
00:22:46,699 --> 00:22:49,076
That dad seems very real.
That's the dad she's drawn,

366
00:22:49,159 --> 00:22:52,288
and he's a heartbeat away
from crashing into this world.

367
00:22:52,413 --> 00:22:54,832
She always got the worst of it
when he was alive.

368
00:22:55,541 --> 00:22:58,961
Doctor, how can a 12-year-old girl
be doing any of this?

369
00:23:01,171 --> 00:23:02,715
Let's find out.

370
00:23:04,884 --> 00:23:06,051
(DOOR OPENING)

371
00:23:19,815 --> 00:23:21,025
Nice one.

372
00:23:31,493 --> 00:23:32,703
-There we go.
-I can't let him...

373
00:23:32,786 --> 00:23:34,371
(WHISPERING) Shh, it's okay. Trust him.

374
00:23:37,207 --> 00:23:38,667
Now we can talk.

375
00:23:39,501 --> 00:23:42,963
(IN SINISTER VOICE) I want Chloe!
Wake her up!

376
00:23:43,047 --> 00:23:46,842
-I want Chloe!
-Who are you?

377
00:23:47,051 --> 00:23:50,554
-I want Chloe Webber!
-What have you done to my little girl?

378
00:23:50,638 --> 00:23:51,847
Doctor, what is it?

379
00:23:51,972 --> 00:23:54,266
I'm speaking to you,

380
00:23:54,350 --> 00:23:56,852
the entity that is using this human child.

381
00:23:58,687 --> 00:24:01,941
I request parley in compliance
with The Shadow Proclamation.

382
00:24:02,024 --> 00:24:05,527
I don't care about shadows or parleyses!

383
00:24:06,153 --> 00:24:07,738
So what do you care about?

384
00:24:07,947 --> 00:24:09,698
I want my friends.

385
00:24:10,574 --> 00:24:12,952
You're lonely, I know.

386
00:24:13,035 --> 00:24:14,536
Identify yourself.

387
00:24:14,620 --> 00:24:16,121
I am one of many.

388
00:24:16,205 --> 00:24:18,457
I travel with my brothers and sisters.

389
00:24:18,540 --> 00:24:23,212
We take an endless journey.
A thousand of your lifetimes.

390
00:24:23,462 --> 00:24:26,632
But now I am alone. I hate it.

391
00:24:26,715 --> 00:24:28,467
It's not fair, and I hate it!

392
00:24:28,550 --> 00:24:29,760
Name yourself.

393
00:24:29,843 --> 00:24:31,303
Isolus.

394
00:24:32,346 --> 00:24:34,723
You're Isolus, of course.

395
00:24:35,391 --> 00:24:38,686
Our journey began in the deep realms,

396
00:24:38,811 --> 00:24:41,188
-when we were a family.
-What's that?

397
00:24:41,271 --> 00:24:43,983
The Isolus mother, drifting in deep space.

398
00:24:44,191 --> 00:24:47,319
See? She jettisons millions
of fledgling spores,

399
00:24:47,403 --> 00:24:48,737
her children.

400
00:24:49,530 --> 00:24:51,991
The Isolus are empathic beings
of intense emotion.

401
00:24:52,074 --> 00:24:54,201
When they're cast off
from their mother, their empathic link,

402
00:24:54,284 --> 00:24:57,037
their need for each other,
is what sustains them.

403
00:24:57,621 --> 00:25:01,000
They need to be together.
They cannot be alone.

404
00:25:01,083 --> 00:25:02,584
Our journey is long.

405
00:25:02,710 --> 00:25:04,837
The Isolus children travel,
each inside a pod.

406
00:25:04,920 --> 00:25:07,965
They ride the heat and energy
of solar tides.

407
00:25:08,882 --> 00:25:12,177
And it takes thousands and thousands
of years for them to grow up.

408
00:25:12,845 --> 00:25:15,764
Thousands of years
just floating through space?

409
00:25:16,390 --> 00:25:18,851
Poor things.
Don't they go mad with boredom?

410
00:25:18,934 --> 00:25:21,145
We play.

411
00:25:21,979 --> 00:25:23,939
You...play?

412
00:25:24,064 --> 00:25:26,108
DOCTOR: While they travel,
they play a game.

413
00:25:26,233 --> 00:25:27,651
They use their ionic power

414
00:25:27,776 --> 00:25:30,779
to literally create make-believe worlds
in which to play.

415
00:25:31,864 --> 00:25:34,658
-In-flight entertainment.
-Helps keep them happy.

416
00:25:35,075 --> 00:25:38,328
While they're happy
they can feed off each other's love.

417
00:25:38,412 --> 00:25:40,789
Without it, they're lost.

418
00:25:43,459 --> 00:25:46,712
-Why did you come to Earth?
-We were too close.

419
00:25:50,132 --> 00:25:52,426
That's a solar flare from your sun.

420
00:25:52,509 --> 00:25:54,261
Would have made a tidal wave
of solar energy

421
00:25:54,344 --> 00:25:56,638
that scattered the Isolus pods.

422
00:25:56,889 --> 00:25:58,474
Only I fell to Earth.

423
00:25:59,016 --> 00:26:03,312
My brothers and sisters are left up there,
and I cannot reach them.

424
00:26:03,937 --> 00:26:07,441
-So alone!
-Your pod crashed?

425
00:26:07,524 --> 00:26:08,650
Where is it?

426
00:26:08,734 --> 00:26:10,235
My pod was drawn to heat.

427
00:26:10,986 --> 00:26:12,988
And I was drawn to Chloe Webber.

428
00:26:17,493 --> 00:26:20,162
She was like me. Alone.

429
00:26:20,662 --> 00:26:23,916
She needed me and I her.

430
00:26:23,999 --> 00:26:26,126
DOCTOR: You empathised with her.

431
00:26:26,627 --> 00:26:29,171
You wanted to be with her
because she was alone like you.

432
00:26:29,296 --> 00:26:30,798
I want my family!

433
00:26:30,881 --> 00:26:32,091
It's not fair!

434
00:26:32,174 --> 00:26:34,802
I understand. You wanna make a family.

435
00:26:34,885 --> 00:26:38,472
But you can't stay in this child. It's wrong.

436
00:26:38,889 --> 00:26:41,266
You can't steal any more friends
for yourself.

437
00:26:41,350 --> 00:26:42,518
I am alone.

438
00:26:42,601 --> 00:26:43,685
(THUDDING)

439
00:26:43,769 --> 00:26:48,398
SINISTER VOICE: I'm coming to hurt you.
I'm coming...

440
00:26:48,482 --> 00:26:50,484
-Trish, how do you calm her?
-TRISH: What?

441
00:26:50,567 --> 00:26:52,319
When she has nightmares, what do you do?

442
00:26:52,402 --> 00:26:54,363
-What do you do?
-I sing to her.

443
00:26:54,488 --> 00:26:55,864
Then start singing.

444
00:26:55,989 --> 00:26:58,700
SINISTER VOICE: Chloe, I'm coming...

445
00:26:58,784 --> 00:27:01,370
# Kookaburra sits in the old gum tree

446
00:27:01,453 --> 00:27:04,498
# Merry merry king of the bush is he #

447
00:27:04,581 --> 00:27:05,666
Chloe!

448
00:27:06,959 --> 00:27:08,544
Chloe!

449
00:27:09,795 --> 00:27:11,505
(SINISTER VOICE FADING)

450
00:27:11,588 --> 00:27:13,799
# ...kookaburra, laugh, kookaburra

451
00:27:13,882 --> 00:27:16,218
# Gay your life must be #

452
00:27:18,804 --> 00:27:20,931
It came to her because she was lonely.

453
00:27:21,598 --> 00:27:23,225
(CRYING) Chloe, I'm sorry.

454
00:27:27,312 --> 00:27:30,816
Chloe usually got the brunt of his temper,
when he'd had a drink.

455
00:27:30,899 --> 00:27:33,402
The day he crashed the car,
I thought we were free.

456
00:27:33,485 --> 00:27:35,070
I thought it was over.

457
00:27:35,571 --> 00:27:38,157
-Did you talk to her about it?
-I didn't want to.

458
00:27:39,408 --> 00:27:42,744
But maybe that's why Chloe feels so alone,

459
00:27:42,828 --> 00:27:45,789
'cause she has all these
terrible dreams about her dad,

460
00:27:45,914 --> 00:27:47,875
but she can't talk to you about them.

461
00:27:47,958 --> 00:27:50,043
Her and the Isolus,

462
00:27:50,127 --> 00:27:52,588
two lonely kids who need each other.

463
00:27:52,671 --> 00:27:54,798
And it won't stop, will it, Doctor?

464
00:27:55,424 --> 00:27:57,676
Just keep pulling kids in.

465
00:27:58,051 --> 00:28:00,053
It's desperate to be loved.

466
00:28:00,387 --> 00:28:03,432
-And it's used to a pretty big family.
-How big?

467
00:28:04,850 --> 00:28:08,103
Say around four billion?

468
00:28:08,770 --> 00:28:12,065
MAN ON TV: ...in and out of central London.
It is remarkable.

469
00:28:12,774 --> 00:28:17,154
The queue started a week ago
for those desperate enough to be inside,

470
00:28:17,279 --> 00:28:18,405
and there are lots of them.

471
00:28:18,488 --> 00:28:21,241
We're expecting
a capacity crowd of 80,000

472
00:28:21,325 --> 00:28:24,786
for this evening's opening ceremony.
I have to say there's been...

473
00:28:24,912 --> 00:28:26,371
We need that pod.

474
00:28:26,455 --> 00:28:28,040
It crashed. Won't it be destroyed?

475
00:28:28,123 --> 00:28:29,625
Well, it's been sucking in
all the heat it can.

476
00:28:29,750 --> 00:28:31,877
Hopefully that should keep it
in a fit state to launch.

477
00:28:31,960 --> 00:28:32,961
It must be close.

478
00:28:33,086 --> 00:28:35,422
It should have a weak energy signature
the Tardis can trace.

479
00:28:35,505 --> 00:28:38,300
Once we find it,
then we can stop the Isolus.

480
00:28:40,010 --> 00:28:42,387
She's running a temperature.

481
00:28:43,180 --> 00:28:47,726
I can't go into that now, Kirsty.
Yes, we've got a doctor.

482
00:28:49,228 --> 00:28:51,021
Yeah, he said he can help her.

483
00:28:51,980 --> 00:28:55,359
We can scan for the same trace
that I picked up from the scribble creature.

484
00:28:55,442 --> 00:28:57,653
Just need to widen the field a bit.

485
00:29:05,869 --> 00:29:07,329
(TARDIS DOOR SHUTTING)

486
00:29:10,791 --> 00:29:14,002
You knew the Isolus was lonely
before it told you. How?

487
00:29:14,253 --> 00:29:16,088
I know what it's like to travel a long way
on your own.

488
00:29:16,171 --> 00:29:18,382
Give me the steino-magnetic... Um...

489
00:29:18,966 --> 00:29:20,092
Thing in your left hand.

490
00:29:20,175 --> 00:29:21,635
Sounds like you're on its side.

491
00:29:21,718 --> 00:29:23,095
I sympathise, that's all.

492
00:29:23,178 --> 00:29:25,681
The Isolus has caused a lot of pain
for these people.

493
00:29:25,764 --> 00:29:30,018
It's a child. That's why it went to Chloe.
Two lonely mixed-up kids.

494
00:29:30,143 --> 00:29:32,980
Feels to me like a temper tantrum
'cause it can't get its own way.

495
00:29:33,063 --> 00:29:35,148
It's scared. Come on, you were a kid once.

496
00:29:35,232 --> 00:29:36,400
-Binary dot.
-Yes.

497
00:29:36,483 --> 00:29:40,529
And I know what kids can be like.
Right little...terrors.

498
00:29:46,368 --> 00:29:49,371
-Gum.
-I've got cousins.

499
00:29:49,454 --> 00:29:51,748
Kids can't have it all their own way.
That's part of being a family.

500
00:29:51,832 --> 00:29:53,959
And what about trying to understand them?

501
00:29:54,626 --> 00:29:58,422
-Easy for you to say, you don't have kids.
-I was a dad once.

502
00:29:58,505 --> 00:30:00,132
What did you say?

503
00:30:01,842 --> 00:30:05,721
I think we're there. Fear. Loneliness.
They're the big ones, Rose.

504
00:30:05,804 --> 00:30:08,807
Some of the most terrible acts ever
committed have been inspired by them.

505
00:30:08,890 --> 00:30:13,145
We're not dealing with something
that wants to conquer or destroy.

506
00:30:13,228 --> 00:30:15,480
There's a lot of things you need
to get across this universe,

507
00:30:15,564 --> 00:30:19,860
warp drive, wormhole refractors.
You know the thing you need most of all?

508
00:30:19,943 --> 00:30:22,029
You need a hand to hold.

509
00:30:24,448 --> 00:30:26,783
No, no, I'm pointing.

510
00:30:28,410 --> 00:30:31,538
DOCTOR: It's the pod! It is in the street!

511
00:30:31,663 --> 00:30:34,166
Everything's coming up Doctor.

512
00:30:40,005 --> 00:30:44,092
Okay, it's like, two inches across.
Dull grey, like a gull's egg, very light.

513
00:30:44,217 --> 00:30:47,637
ROSE: So these pods, they travel
from some sun using heat, yeah?

514
00:30:47,763 --> 00:30:49,639
So it's not all about love and stuff.

515
00:30:49,723 --> 00:30:51,016
Doesn't the pod just need heat?

516
00:30:51,099 --> 00:30:52,142
(CRASHING)

517
00:30:54,102 --> 00:30:55,395
Doctor?

518
00:30:58,065 --> 00:30:59,608
Doctor!

519
00:31:04,112 --> 00:31:06,656
It's okay, I've taken all the pencils off her.

520
00:31:11,286 --> 00:31:13,288
Leave me alone!

521
00:31:13,372 --> 00:31:16,792
I want to be with Chloe Webber!
I love Chloe Webber!

522
00:31:16,958 --> 00:31:19,461
-Bring him back now.
-No!

523
00:31:20,212 --> 00:31:22,381
Don't you realise what you've done?

524
00:31:22,464 --> 00:31:24,674
He was the only one who could help you.
Now bring him back!

525
00:31:24,758 --> 00:31:27,886
Leave me alone! I love Chloe Webber!

526
00:31:32,224 --> 00:31:33,767
I know.

527
00:31:36,061 --> 00:31:37,479
I know.

528
00:31:39,147 --> 00:31:42,109
Doctor, if you can hear me,
I'm gonna get you out of there.

529
00:31:42,192 --> 00:31:43,902
I'll find the pod.

530
00:31:44,653 --> 00:31:46,405
Don't leave her alone, no matter what.

531
00:31:46,488 --> 00:31:49,699
MAN ON TV: ...the torchbearer getting
even closer to the Olympic Stadium,

532
00:31:49,783 --> 00:31:52,661
heading down the Strand, before
turning east along the Embankment...

533
00:31:53,912 --> 00:31:57,499
Heat. They travel on heat.

534
00:31:57,916 --> 00:31:59,668
Look at this finish.

535
00:31:59,751 --> 00:32:04,005
Smooth as a baby's bottom.
Not a bump or a lump.

536
00:32:04,172 --> 00:32:07,968
Kel, was there anything in this street in
the last few days giving off a lot of heat?

537
00:32:08,051 --> 00:32:10,512
I mean, you could eat your dinner off this.

538
00:32:10,679 --> 00:32:13,849
Beautiful. So, you tell me
why the other one's got a lump in it

539
00:32:13,974 --> 00:32:17,352
when I gave it the same love
and craftsmanship as I did this one.

540
00:32:17,436 --> 00:32:21,106
Well, when you've worked it out,
put it in a big book about tarmacking.

541
00:32:21,189 --> 00:32:24,234
But before you do that, think back six days.

542
00:32:24,609 --> 00:32:26,611
Six days.

543
00:32:26,695 --> 00:32:28,655
When I was laying this the first time round.

544
00:32:28,738 --> 00:32:29,781
What?

545
00:32:29,865 --> 00:32:32,826
Well, that's when I filled in this pothole
for the first time.

546
00:32:32,909 --> 00:32:35,370
-Six days ago.
-Yeah.

547
00:32:35,495 --> 00:32:37,497
Hot, fresh tar.

548
00:32:37,873 --> 00:32:40,167
Blended to a secret council recipe.

549
00:32:40,250 --> 00:32:42,419
No, I don't keep it in the van.

550
00:32:43,628 --> 00:32:46,256
Hey! That's a council van. Out.

551
00:32:48,175 --> 00:32:49,593
Whoa! Wait... Wait a minute!

552
00:32:49,676 --> 00:32:52,262
You've just removed a council axe
from a council van.

553
00:32:52,387 --> 00:32:53,555
Put it back! No, don't, wait.

554
00:32:53,638 --> 00:32:56,057
If it's going in the van, that's my van.
Gimme the axe!

555
00:32:56,141 --> 00:32:59,895
Wait! No! No! You... Stop!

556
00:33:00,770 --> 00:33:03,815
You just took a council axe
from a council van,

557
00:33:03,899 --> 00:33:06,276
and now you're digging up a council road!

558
00:33:06,401 --> 00:33:08,361
I'm reporting you to the council!

559
00:33:12,407 --> 00:33:15,994
It went for the hottest thing
in the street, yeah? Your tar.

560
00:33:16,077 --> 00:33:18,580
-What is it?
-It's a spaceship.

561
00:33:18,663 --> 00:33:20,749
Not a council spaceship, I'm afraid.

562
00:33:21,249 --> 00:33:24,085
MAN ON TV: ...joined us, welcome.
We're live on BBC News 24.

563
00:33:24,169 --> 00:33:27,881
The opening ceremony
of the London Olympics of 2012.

564
00:33:27,964 --> 00:33:30,717
Well underway,
athletes from all over the world,

565
00:33:30,800 --> 00:33:34,012
streaming into the stadium right now.
They all have their dreams.

566
00:33:34,095 --> 00:33:36,932
They've all put in years of hard work...

567
00:33:37,933 --> 00:33:39,476
I found it!

568
00:33:39,851 --> 00:33:43,772
Don't know what to do with it, but maybe
the Isolus will just hop on board.

569
00:33:44,147 --> 00:33:46,149
Hang on, I told you not to leave her.

570
00:33:46,942 --> 00:33:50,111
MAN ON TV: My God!
Uh, what's going on here?

571
00:33:50,237 --> 00:33:53,114
I don't care if you got Snow White
and the Seven Dwarves buried under there,

572
00:33:53,198 --> 00:33:54,824
-you don't go digging...
-Shut up and look!

573
00:33:54,950 --> 00:33:56,159
The crowd has vanished.

574
00:33:56,243 --> 00:33:59,871
Um, they're gone, everyone has gone.

575
00:33:59,955 --> 00:34:05,126
Thousands of people have just gone,
uh, right in front of my eyes.

576
00:34:05,210 --> 00:34:07,837
Um, it's impossible.

577
00:34:07,921 --> 00:34:12,175
Bob, can we join you in the box? Bob?

578
00:34:13,885 --> 00:34:17,222
-Not you too, Bob!
-ROSE: A stadium won't be enough.

579
00:34:17,305 --> 00:34:20,892
The Isolus has
four billion brothers and sisters.

580
00:34:22,435 --> 00:34:27,440
Over 80,000 spectators
and 30,000 athletes...

581
00:34:27,524 --> 00:34:29,192
Not enough.

582
00:34:29,651 --> 00:34:32,904
They're gone, all of those people.

583
00:34:33,863 --> 00:34:37,826
Uh, it's a terrible, terrible turn of events...

584
00:34:37,909 --> 00:34:42,289
We won't be alone, Chloe Webber.
We'll have all of them.

585
00:34:42,372 --> 00:34:46,126
And then we'll never feel alone ever again.

586
00:34:48,461 --> 00:34:51,548
TRISH: Chloe?
ROSE: Chloe, it's Rose! Open the door!

587
00:34:54,467 --> 00:34:56,469
We found your ship!
We can send you home.

588
00:34:56,553 --> 00:34:58,847
-Chloe!
-Open up!

589
00:34:58,972 --> 00:35:00,432
Right, stand back.

590
00:35:00,515 --> 00:35:02,976
SINISTER VOICE: I'm coming to hurt you.

591
00:35:08,273 --> 00:35:12,235
I'm coming. Coming to hurt you, Chloe.

592
00:35:16,448 --> 00:35:19,451
-Chloe!
-I'm coming to hurt you!

593
00:35:20,076 --> 00:35:21,828
-I'm coming.
-I've gotta stop her.

594
00:35:23,663 --> 00:35:26,958
If you stop Chloe Webber, I will let him out.

595
00:35:27,042 --> 00:35:29,461
We will let him out. Together.

596
00:35:29,544 --> 00:35:32,422
I cannot be alone! It's not fair!

597
00:35:32,505 --> 00:35:33,548
(GROWLING)

598
00:35:33,673 --> 00:35:35,884
-Look, I've got your pod!
-The pod is dead!

599
00:35:36,009 --> 00:35:38,762
-No, no. It only needs heat.
-It needs more than heat.

600
00:35:38,887 --> 00:35:39,929
What then?

601
00:35:40,055 --> 00:35:43,391
I'm not being funny or nothing,
but that picture just moved.

602
00:35:44,059 --> 00:35:46,394
And that one!

603
00:35:49,606 --> 00:35:51,775
She didn't draw that, he did.

604
00:35:53,193 --> 00:35:55,320
But it needs more than heat, Doctor.

605
00:35:55,445 --> 00:35:59,741
MAN ON TV: ...still on its way.
I suppose it's much more than a torch now.

606
00:35:59,866 --> 00:36:03,703
It's a beacon. It's a beacon
of hope and fortitude and courage.

607
00:36:03,870 --> 00:36:07,290
-And it's a beacon of love.
-Love.

608
00:36:07,582 --> 00:36:09,542
So let's have a look from the helicopter.

609
00:36:09,626 --> 00:36:13,254
-There we go, the torchbearer...
-I know how to charge up the pod.

610
00:36:13,338 --> 00:36:15,298
...past Dame Kelly Holmes Close...

611
00:36:16,675 --> 00:36:19,678
(PEOPLE CHEERING)

612
00:36:29,938 --> 00:36:32,232
-Sorry, you'll have to watch from here.
-No, I've gotta get closer!

613
00:36:32,315 --> 00:36:34,484
-No way.
-I can stop this from happening!

614
00:36:34,609 --> 00:36:35,985
SINISTER VOICE: Chloe.

615
00:36:36,069 --> 00:36:37,987
-Chloe.
-I'm coming to hurt you.

616
00:36:38,071 --> 00:36:39,114
My baby!

617
00:36:39,197 --> 00:36:42,450
-You're not going to hurt her again!
-Chloe! I'm coming!

618
00:36:44,619 --> 00:36:46,705
(POD BEEPING)

619
00:36:47,956 --> 00:36:49,874
You felt it, didn't you?

620
00:36:58,633 --> 00:37:00,135
(WHISPERING) Feel the love.

621
00:37:15,817 --> 00:37:17,527
(ROSE CHEERING)

622
00:37:21,114 --> 00:37:23,283
I can go home.

623
00:37:23,366 --> 00:37:25,452
Goodbye, Chloe Webber.

624
00:37:26,161 --> 00:37:27,829
I love you.

625
00:37:36,045 --> 00:37:39,132
-Mum?
-I'm here.

626
00:37:39,424 --> 00:37:40,842
Mummy!

627
00:37:44,846 --> 00:37:46,973
Nice one! You did it!

628
00:37:48,558 --> 00:37:50,935
What was it you did?

629
00:37:53,021 --> 00:37:54,105
Yeah!

630
00:38:04,365 --> 00:38:05,408
Mummy!

631
00:38:05,533 --> 00:38:07,202
Oh, Jane!

632
00:38:12,040 --> 00:38:13,416
Doctor?

633
00:38:13,541 --> 00:38:14,834
MAN: He's back now.

634
00:38:17,128 --> 00:38:21,508
I don't know who you are, or what you did,
but thank you, darling.

635
00:38:22,383 --> 00:38:25,220
And thank that man from me, too.

636
00:38:27,430 --> 00:38:29,849
Where is he? He should be here.

637
00:38:33,102 --> 00:38:35,396
All the drawings have come to life.

638
00:38:37,315 --> 00:38:38,691
That means all of them.

639
00:38:38,775 --> 00:38:39,943
(SINISTER VOICE GROWLING)

640
00:38:40,068 --> 00:38:41,319
Oh no...

641
00:38:50,912 --> 00:38:53,164
-Trish, get out!
-I can't. The door's stuck.

642
00:38:53,248 --> 00:38:54,833
-Is the Doctor in there?
-I don't think so.

643
00:38:54,916 --> 00:38:56,584
Mummy!

644
00:38:56,709 --> 00:38:58,294
(THUDDING)

645
00:38:58,419 --> 00:39:01,381
SINISTER VOICE: I'm coming to hurt you!

646
00:39:01,464 --> 00:39:04,759
-Please, Dad, no more.
-Chloe!

647
00:39:04,884 --> 00:39:07,178
Chloe, listen to me.
It isn't real like the others.

648
00:39:07,262 --> 00:39:09,305
It's just energy left over by the Isolus.

649
00:39:09,430 --> 00:39:11,891
-But you can get rid of it, Chloe.
-Help us!

650
00:39:12,016 --> 00:39:13,852
Oh, it's 'cause you're so scared
that he's real.

651
00:39:13,935 --> 00:39:16,020
But you can get shot of him, Chloe.

652
00:39:16,104 --> 00:39:18,439
-Mummy!
-ROSE: You can do it, Chloe!

653
00:39:18,523 --> 00:39:19,524
I can't!

654
00:39:19,607 --> 00:39:22,652
SINISTER VOICE: Chloe! I'm coming!

655
00:39:22,777 --> 00:39:23,862
I can't!

656
00:39:23,945 --> 00:39:26,865
-I'm coming!
-I can't!

657
00:39:26,948 --> 00:39:31,536
-I'm coming! Chloe!
-Mummy!

658
00:39:31,619 --> 00:39:36,165
I'm with you, Chloe. You're not alone.
You'll never be alone again.

659
00:39:36,291 --> 00:39:39,294
-I'm coming to hurt you.
-ROSE: Sing again. Chloe, sing!

660
00:39:39,377 --> 00:39:40,545
Chloe! Chloe!

661
00:39:40,628 --> 00:39:42,046
# Kookaburra sits...

662
00:39:42,130 --> 00:39:44,382
-Chloe!
-# ...gum tree

663
00:39:44,465 --> 00:39:47,719
-Chloe!
-# Merry merry king of the bush #

664
00:39:47,802 --> 00:39:49,762
Chloe, I'm coming to hurt you.

665
00:39:49,846 --> 00:39:53,558
BOTH: # Laugh, kookaburra,
laugh, kookaburra

666
00:39:53,641 --> 00:39:56,728
# Gay your life must be

667
00:39:56,978 --> 00:40:00,064
# Laugh, kookaburra, laugh, kookaburra

668
00:40:00,148 --> 00:40:01,816
# Gay your life must be #

669
00:40:01,941 --> 00:40:03,318
(SINISTER VOICE FADING)

670
00:40:03,443 --> 00:40:06,487
# Kookaburra sits in the old gum tree

671
00:40:06,654 --> 00:40:09,991
# Merry merry king of the bush is he

672
00:40:10,116 --> 00:40:13,286
# Laugh, kookaburra, laugh, kookaburra

673
00:40:13,369 --> 00:40:16,122
# Gay your life must be #

674
00:40:21,753 --> 00:40:24,213
Maybe he's gone somewhere.

675
00:40:27,008 --> 00:40:29,135
Who's gonna hold his hand now?

676
00:40:35,516 --> 00:40:40,313
MAN ON TV: Just look at this. Utterly
incredible scenes at the Olympic Stadium.

677
00:40:40,396 --> 00:40:44,359
80,000 athletes and spectators,
they disappeared, they've come back.

678
00:40:44,442 --> 00:40:45,610
They've returned.

679
00:40:45,693 --> 00:40:48,363
They've re-appeared. It's quite incredible.

680
00:40:48,488 --> 00:40:50,031
But, Bob, this will certainly prompt...

681
00:40:50,114 --> 00:40:53,785
80,000 people. So where's the Doctor?
I need him!

682
00:40:53,868 --> 00:40:56,955
But hang on. The torchbearer seems to be
in a bit of trouble.

683
00:40:57,038 --> 00:41:01,209
We did see a flash of lightning earlier
that seemed to strike him.

684
00:41:01,292 --> 00:41:04,712
Maybe he's injured.
He's definitely in trouble.

685
00:41:05,421 --> 00:41:09,384
This mean that the Olympic dream is dead?

686
00:41:10,343 --> 00:41:11,636
Doctor!

687
00:41:12,720 --> 00:41:13,846
There's a mystery man.

688
00:41:13,930 --> 00:41:17,100
He's picked up the flame,
and we've no idea who he is.

689
00:41:18,226 --> 00:41:20,603
He's carrying the flame,
yes, he's carrying the flame,

690
00:41:20,687 --> 00:41:22,689
and no one wants to stop him.

691
00:41:22,814 --> 00:41:26,109
It's more than a flame now, Bob.
It's more than heat and light.

692
00:41:26,192 --> 00:41:28,903
It's hope, and it's courage, and it's love.

693
00:41:28,987 --> 00:41:30,905
(SPECTATORS CHEERING)

694
00:41:36,911 --> 00:41:38,287
(WHOOPING)

695
00:41:49,757 --> 00:41:54,679
Go on. Join your brothers and sisters.
They'll be waiting!

696
00:41:59,183 --> 00:42:01,602
(CHEERING)

697
00:42:22,915 --> 00:42:23,958
Cake?

698
00:42:26,961 --> 00:42:28,629
(LAUGHING)

699
00:42:30,715 --> 00:42:32,467
Top banana!

700
00:42:36,596 --> 00:42:41,476
I can't stress this enough.
Ball bearings you can eat. Masterpiece!

701
00:42:43,978 --> 00:42:47,857
-I thought I'd lost you.
-Nah. Not on a night like this.

702
00:42:48,483 --> 00:42:51,611
This is a night for lost things being found.
Come on.

703
00:42:51,694 --> 00:42:53,654
What now?

704
00:42:53,738 --> 00:42:56,282
I wanna go to the Games,
it's what we came for.

705
00:42:56,365 --> 00:42:58,451
Go on. Give us a clue.

706
00:42:58,785 --> 00:43:00,661
Which events do we do well in?

707
00:43:00,745 --> 00:43:02,538
Well, I will tell you this,

708
00:43:02,622 --> 00:43:05,958
Papua New Guinea surprised everyone
in the shot put.

709
00:43:06,042 --> 00:43:09,170
Really? You're joking, aren't you?

710
00:43:09,253 --> 00:43:12,006
Doctor? Are you serious, or are you joking?

711
00:43:12,090 --> 00:43:13,174
Wait and see.

712
00:43:14,092 --> 00:43:15,384
(PEOPLE EXCLAIMING)

713
00:43:16,803 --> 00:43:19,347
You know what?
They keep on trying to split us up,

714
00:43:19,472 --> 00:43:21,015
but they never ever will.

715
00:43:21,516 --> 00:43:24,060
Never say, "Never ever."

716
00:43:25,520 --> 00:43:27,939
Nah, we'll always be okay, you and me.

717
00:43:28,022 --> 00:43:29,524
(FIRECRACKERS BURSTING)

718
00:43:30,149 --> 00:43:32,193
Don't you reckon, Doctor?

719
00:43:33,361 --> 00:43:35,780
Something in the air. Something coming.

720
00:43:35,863 --> 00:43:37,865
What?

721
00:43:38,491 --> 00:43:40,368
A storm's approaching.

722
00:43:49,001 --> 00:43:51,546
ROSE.: This is a story of war on Earth.

723
00:43:51,629 --> 00:43:57,301
DRAMATIC VOICE: The valiant child
who will die in battle so very soon.

724
00:43:57,385 --> 00:43:59,011
ROSE: It said I was gonna die in battle.

725
00:43:59,095 --> 00:44:00,304
DOCTOR: Then it lied.

726
00:44:00,388 --> 00:44:03,724
Welcome to Torchwood.

727
00:44:04,016 --> 00:44:06,018
Woke up one morning,
and there they all were.

728
00:44:06,102 --> 00:44:07,770
Ghosts everywhere.

729
00:44:07,895 --> 00:44:09,814
If I'm the enemy,
does that mean I'm the prisoner?

730
00:44:09,897 --> 00:44:11,065
Oh, yes.

731
00:44:11,732 --> 00:44:13,693
Oi! Where are you taking that?

732
00:44:13,776 --> 00:44:15,236
If it's alien, it's ours.

733
00:44:15,361 --> 00:44:16,737
We've got a problem down here.

734
00:44:17,071 --> 00:44:18,322
MAN: Yvonne, can you hear me?

735
00:44:18,406 --> 00:44:19,991
You send that thing back into hell.

736
00:44:20,074 --> 00:44:23,953
The Doctor, lording it over us, assuming
alien authority over the rights of man.

737
00:44:24,036 --> 00:44:26,330
DOCTOR: They're bleeding through
the fault lines.

738
00:44:26,414 --> 00:44:29,417
Walking from their world, across the void,
and into yours.

739
00:44:31,294 --> 00:44:32,628
You can't stop us, Doctor.

740
00:44:32,753 --> 00:44:34,005
DOCTOR: This world is colliding
with another.

741
00:44:34,088 --> 00:44:35,423
Positions!

742
00:44:35,756 --> 00:44:37,175
What are they?

743
00:44:38,759 --> 00:44:39,927
Cybermen.

744
00:44:41,220 --> 00:44:42,597
(SCREAMING)

745
00:44:43,931 --> 00:44:45,516
ROSE: And that's when it all ended.

746
00:44:47,018 --> 00:44:50,021
This is the last story I'll ever tell.

